data.name: richTextBox1.Text
data.value:
##################### ### Mouse Engines ### ##################### A mouse engine is a handler for the mouse, there are serveral build in handlers. There are various configurations that can be combined with each engine.
Why are there more than one mouse handler? There are many different games as there are stars and many of them require different ways of playing them. And frankly some of our engines suck so we try to improve or remake them.
The current engines are: Percentage Percentage + Relative Raw Input Raw Input + Sensitivity None
Percentage ---------- This engine works by trying to translate your mouse movement as a percentage and applying that number to the controller's analog location, it seems good on paper but does not perform that very well
Percentage + Relative ---------- This move will allow you to move your mouse around and keep it in the current location as before, hence the relative movement. When you move your mouse the sticks location stays the same and is incremented / decremented on each movement. This derives the values from the Percentage engine so it may also appear to be segmented.
Raw Input ---------- This will take the changes (in pixels) of your mouse movement from last the capture and just apply it straight onto the joystick, this will change depending on your monitor size, Smaller monitors eg less than 1080p may not have that much of a great effect.
Raw Input + Sensitivity ---------- This will take the same as Raw Input but will multiply the pixels by the sensitivity values set in the config.
None ---------- Disables the mouse movement
